  "articleSummary": "The article is a practical, tutorial‑style recount of upgrading an eight‑year‑old Gatsby v1 blog to a modern static‑site stack, aimed at developers who maintain personal or small‑scale content sites. The author explains why they selected Astro—citing its simple API, lack of cloud or framework bias, and fast build tooling—and then outlines the accompanying stack (ShadcnUI, Tailwind, MDX, Pagefind, Utterances, Netlify) while noting specific “regrets” and lessons learned (e.g., styling quirks, Tailwind trade‑offs). Throughout, the piece uses a “journey” metaphor and side‑by‑side comparison tables to contrast Astro’s `.astro` components with client‑side frameworks, emphasizing the benefits of build‑time rendering, minimal JavaScript, and easy deployment. The tone blends instructional guidance with personal reflection, making it useful for developers evaluating static‑site generators or planning similar migrations.",
